{% capture newsroom_page_fallback %}
  {% case newsroom_page_kind %}
    {% when 'about' %}
      <h2>Who is behind this site</h2>
      <p>This publication is built around the reporting and editorial judgment of Shadab "Sha" Chow. The site exists as an independent journalism platform focused on breaking news, public accountability, public safety, civil rights, corruption, cyber crime, white-collar crime, criminal networks, and reader-submitted material with clear public-interest value.</p>
      <p>While the reporting voice across the site is collective and publication-focused, the work is anchored by a named publisher who is responsible for story selection, verification, updates, and corrections.</p>

      <h3>What the newsroom is trying to do</h3>
      <p>The mission is to report what happened, explain why it matters, verify before amplifying, and correct the record when facts change. That means slowing down when claims are shaky, identifying allegations as allegations, and giving readers enough sourcing and context to evaluate the work directly.</p>

      <h3>How the work is approached</h3>
      <p>This site is not a law-enforcement agency, not a government office, and not a political campaign. It is an independent publisher. Reporting may draw on public records, court filings, official statements, interviews, documents, verified open-source material, and reader-submitted tips, but final editorial judgment remains human and accountable.</p>

      <h3>What readers should review next</h3>
      <p>If you want the detailed policy framework behind the work, review <a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a>, <a href="{{ corrections_url }}">Corrections Policy</a>, <a href="{{ legal_url }}">Legal and Advertising</a>, and <a href="{{ privacy_url }}">Privacy Policy</a>. For topic scope, see <a href="{{ investigate_url }}">What We Investigate</a>.</p>

    {% when 'archives' %}
      <h2>How to use the archive</h2>
      <p>The archive exists so readers can review older reporting, compare early accounts with later updates, and understand how the public record developed over time. Not every archived item reflects the latest known facts, which is why dated coverage should be read together with newer reporting, corrections, and follow-up stories where available.</p>

      <h3>Developing records can change</h3>
      <p>Breaking-news coverage often begins before every fact is settled. Arrests are not convictions. Official statements can change. Court cases evolve. New documents can clarify or undermine earlier claims. Archived posts should be read with that reality in mind.</p>

      <h3>How older reporting is handled</h3>
      <p>When material errors are found, the goal is to correct the record clearly and responsibly. Some older items may also carry updates, clarifications, or context notes when later reporting materially changes what a reader should understand about the story.</p>

      <h3>Where to go next</h3>
      <p>For current reporting, visit <a href="/blogs/breaking-news">Breaking News</a>. For standards and correction requests, review <a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a> and <a href="{{ corrections_url }}">Corrections Policy</a>. For the newsroom's coverage scope, see <a href="{{ investigate_url }}">What We Investigate</a>.</p>

    {% when 'standards' %}
      <h2>Mission and public-interest focus</h2>
      <p>We report public-interest stories with care, independence, and accountability. The goal is to help readers understand what happened, why it matters, and what facts are confirmed at the time of publication.</p>
      <p>The site focuses on breaking news, public accountability, public safety, civil rights, government accountability, corruption, cyber crime, white-collar crime, criminal networks, extremism and public safety, source documents, and reader-submitted tips.</p>
      <p>The mission is simple: report what happened, explain why it matters, verify before amplifying, and correct the record when facts change.</p>

      <h3>Verification before amplification</h3>
      <p>Speed matters in breaking news, but accuracy matters more. We aim to verify significant claims before repeating them and to show readers what is confirmed, what is alleged, what comes from official sources, and what is still developing.</p>
      <p>Verification may involve public records, court filings, direct evidence, official statements, interviews, published reporting, source material, images, video, location details, archived pages, or other corroborating information.</p>
      <p>Not every story begins with the same level of proof. When information is incomplete, the story should say so plainly.</p>

      <h3>Confirmed facts vs allegations</h3>
      <p>Allegations are identified as allegations unless and until they are confirmed through reliable records, official statements, court filings, direct evidence, or other credible sourcing.</p>
      <p>An accusation is not proof. An arrest is not a conviction. A lawsuit is not a final finding. Stories involving claims, accusations, investigations, or criminal allegations should distinguish carefully between what is asserted and what is established.</p>

      <h3>Official statements and public records</h3>
      <p>Official statements are identified as official statements, not as automatic proof. Public records can provide important context, but records also have limits and may require follow-up reporting, additional sourcing, or clarification.</p>
      <p>Where possible, stories should make clear whether information comes from law enforcement, a government agency, a court filing, a public document, a witness, a subject of the story, or another source.</p>

      <h3>Reader-submitted tips and evidence</h3>
      <p>Readers may submit tips, documents, images, links, and other material through the site. Submitted material may help shape coverage, but submission does not guarantee publication, response, follow-up, confidentiality, anonymity, or legal protection.</p>
      <p>Submitted material may be reviewed for authenticity, relevance, newsworthiness, privacy concerns, safety concerns, legal risk, and public-interest value. We may use submitted material as a lead, as background, as evidence to verify, or not at all.</p>
      <p>By design, the site tries to avoid rewarding rumor, hoaxes, manipulated media, or unsupported claims.</p>

      <h3>Sensitive reporting standards</h3>
      <p>Some stories involve crime, violence, abuse, minors, victims, hate incidents, extremism or public-safety threats, private individuals, disturbing material, or traumatic events. These stories can carry real consequences for people who are named, shown, or affected.</p>
      <p>We aim to handle sensitive topics with restraint. That may include limiting graphic detail, redacting personal information, avoiding unnecessary repetition of harmful imagery, using viewer-discretion labels, declining to publish certain material, or withholding identifying details when the public-interest case is weak.</p>
      <p>Coverage should not glorify perpetrators, encourage harassment, or present spectacle as reporting.</p>

      <h3>Images and visual material</h3>
      <p>Images and visual material can clarify a story, but they can also mislead or cause unnecessary harm when used carelessly. We may crop, blur, excerpt, contextualize, or decline visual material based on editorial judgment.</p>
      <p>Viewer-discretion or context labels may be used when imagery involves violence, injury, death, graphic scenes, distressing behavior, or other sensitive material.</p>

      <h3>Opinion, analysis, and commentary</h3>
      <p>Some pieces may include analysis, commentary, or point of view. When that happens, the piece should still rest on identifiable facts, fair description, and a clear separation between what is known and what is being interpreted.</p>
      <p>Opinion should not be presented as confirmed reporting.</p>

      <h3>Conflicts of interest and independence</h3>
      <p>This site is an independent publisher. Advertising, sponsorships, affiliate links, donations, and other monetization relationships do not control editorial judgment, story selection, conclusions, or corrections.</p>
      <p>If a relationship could materially affect how readers understand a story, the site may disclose it or decline the coverage. Paid placements should be labeled and kept distinct from editorial reporting.</p>

      <h3>AI-assisted tools</h3>
      <p>We may use AI-assisted or automated tools for research support, drafting assistance, formatting, transcription, translation, summarization, workflow organization, or proofreading.</p>
      <p>Final editorial judgment remains human. AI tools should not be used to invent facts, fabricate quotes, manufacture evidence, or misrepresent reporting.</p>

      <h3>Updates and corrections</h3>
      <p>Stories may be updated as new information becomes available. Material errors should be corrected clearly. Clarifications, corrections, editor's notes, or follow-up reporting may be added when facts change or the record becomes clearer.</p>
      <p>For correction requests or editorial concerns, use the <a href="{{ corrections_url }}">Corrections Policy</a> and <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> pages.</p>

      <h3>Editorial concerns</h3>
      <p>Readers may contact the site about sourcing, context, fairness, privacy concerns, sensitive material, or possible inaccuracies. Not every message will receive a response, but credible, evidence-backed concerns are taken seriously.</p>

    {% when 'corrections' %}
      <h2>Accuracy and the public record</h2>
      <p>Accuracy is central to reader trust. When facts change or an error is identified, our goal is to correct the record clearly and responsibly.</p>
      <p>Corrections work is part of journalism, not a side task. Breaking stories evolve, records change, and new evidence can materially alter what a reader should understand about a story.</p>

      <h3>How to request a correction</h3>
      <p>Use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page to request a correction, clarification, or review of a published item.</p>
      <p>Helpful requests usually include the page URL, headline, the specific statement or image at issue, what appears to be wrong or incomplete, and any supporting records, links, or source material.</p>

      <h3>What to include</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>The article or page URL</li>
        <li>The headline or title</li>
        <li>The specific sentence, claim, image, caption, or timeline detail at issue</li>
        <li>A short explanation of the problem</li>
        <li>Any public records, documents, links, or other evidence that supports your request</li>
        <li>Your contact information, if you want a response</li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Correction vs clarification vs update</h3>
      <p>A correction is used for a factual error. A clarification is used when wording is technically accurate but incomplete, vague, or likely to mislead. An update is used when a developing story changes because new facts emerge after publication.</p>
      <p>An editor's note may be used when readers need context about a material change, dispute, or limitation in the reporting.</p>

      <h3>Removal requests</h3>
      <p>A request for removal is not the same as a correction request. The site may review requests involving privacy, safety, age of information, or changed legal circumstances, but accurate public-interest reporting is not removed automatically simply because it is uncomfortable, negative, or unwelcome.</p>
      <p>The site does not guarantee removal, de-indexing, or rewriting of accurate reporting.</p>

      <h3>Developing stories</h3>
      <p>Some stories are published while facts are still emerging. In those cases, readers should expect that later reporting may add context, revise timelines, include official responses, clarify allegations, or correct early errors.</p>
      <p>Developing stories may change as new facts emerge. That is a reason to update the record, not to leave inaccurate information in place.</p>

      <h3>Visible corrections</h3>
      <p>When an error is material, the correction should be visible in a way that helps readers understand what changed. That may include corrected text, a note, an updated timestamp, or follow-up reporting depending on the circumstances.</p>

      <h3>Requests the site may decline</h3>
      <p>The site may decline requests that are unsupported, abusive, repetitive without new evidence, misleading, or aimed at suppressing accurate public-interest reporting rather than correcting a factual problem.</p>

      <h3>No guaranteed response</h3>
      <p>Not every request will receive a personal reply. Some requests may be reviewed and resolved without direct follow-up, and some may be declined based on the available evidence and editorial judgment.</p>

      <h3>Contact path</h3>
      <p>For correction requests, use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page. For broader editorial standards, see <a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a>.</p>

    {% when 'legal' %}
      <h2>Independent publisher disclosure</h2>
      <p>We operate this site as an independent journalism and public-accountability platform. The site exists to publish reporting, analysis, commentary, and policy information in the public interest.</p>
      <p>The site is not a law-enforcement agency, government office, political campaign, or legal service. It is a publisher.</p>

      <h3>Informational and journalistic purpose</h3>
      <p>Content on this site is provided for journalistic, informational, and editorial purposes. Stories may involve public records, allegations, official statements, reader-submitted material, commentary, or developing facts that can change over time.</p>
      <p>Readers should not treat the site as a substitute for professional legal, financial, medical, security, or emergency advice.</p>

      <h3>No professional advice</h3>
      <p>Nothing on this site is legal advice, financial advice, medical advice, safety advice, or professional consulting. If you need professional help, seek a qualified advisor or the appropriate emergency or public service resource.</p>

      <h3>Advertising, sponsorship, and affiliate disclosure</h3>
      <p>The site may use advertising, sponsorships, affiliate links, reader-support tools, newsletters, or other monetization methods to support operations.</p>
      <p>Advertising, sponsorships, affiliate links, or other monetization relationships do not control our editorial judgment, story selection, conclusions, or corrections.</p>
      <p>Paid placements should be labeled clearly enough that readers can distinguish them from reporting.</p>

      <h3>Editorial independence</h3>
      <p>Sponsors and advertisers do not buy editorial coverage, favorable conclusions, story removal, or influence over corrections. Coverage decisions remain editorial decisions.</p>

      <h3>External links and third-party platforms</h3>
      <p>The site may link to or embed outside platforms, public records, social media posts, documents, maps, videos, or third-party resources. Those third parties operate under their own rules, privacy practices, and availability.</p>
      <p>The site is not responsible for every change, outage, or policy decision made by an outside platform.</p>

      <h3>Sensitive reporting topics</h3>
      <p>Coverage may include crime, public safety, civil rights, corruption, fraud, violence, extremism, disturbing material, or other sensitive topics. Editorial care, context, and viewer-discretion labels may be used where appropriate.</p>

      <h3>User-submitted tips and materials</h3>
      <p>Readers may submit tips, documents, images, videos, and other material through the site. Submission does not guarantee publication, response, investigation, legal protection, confidentiality, or compensation.</p>
      <p>Do not assume a web form, email, or routine site tool provides anonymity, encryption, or privilege.</p>

      <h3>No guarantee of monetization or platform approval</h3>
      <p>The site does not guarantee advertiser participation, sponsorship acceptance, ad placement, monetization, search visibility, or advertising-platform approval. Advertising policies and publisher-platform decisions may change without notice.</p>

      <h3>Contact path</h3>
      <p>For general questions, legal or policy concerns, or advertising disclosures, use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page. Related pages include <a href="{{ advertise_url }}">Advertise / Sponsor</a>, <a href="{{ privacy_url }}">Privacy Policy</a>, and <a href="{{ terms_url }}">Terms of Use</a>.</p>

    {% when 'privacy' %}
      <h2>Who this policy is for</h2>
      <p>This Privacy Policy explains, in plain English, how information may be handled on a publisher site built on Shopify and used for reporting, contact forms, tip submissions, analytics, advertising, newsletters, embedded media, and related site operations.</p>
      <p>The site aims to be transparent about data practices, but it does not promise perfect privacy, anonymity, or security.</p>

      <h3>Information you provide voluntarily</h3>
      <p>You may choose to provide information when you contact the site, submit a tip, request a correction, sign up for updates, ask about sponsorships, or send documents, links, photos, videos, or other materials.</p>
      <p>That information may include your name, email address, phone number, organization, message content, uploaded or linked materials, and any other details you choose to provide.</p>

      <h3>Tip submissions and contact forms</h3>
      <p>If you submit a tip or contact the site, the information you send may be reviewed, stored, verified, summarized, rejected, archived, or used in connection with reporting and site operations.</p>
      <p>Submitting information does not guarantee confidentiality, anonymity, encryption, legal privilege, publication, or a response.</p>
      <p>Do not send highly sensitive information unless you understand the limits of ordinary web forms and email.</p>

      <h3>Newsletter or email signup</h3>
      <p>If newsletter or email signup features are active, your email address and related list-management data may be processed by the site's email service provider to send updates, manage unsubscribes, and measure delivery or engagement.</p>

      <h3>Comments or community features</h3>
      <p>If comments or community tools are enabled now or later, information you post through those tools may be stored, moderated, published, removed, or reviewed for abuse prevention and community safety.</p>

      <h3>Analytics and performance data</h3>
      <p>Like most websites, the site may collect or receive technical information about visits, devices, browsers, referring pages, on-site behavior, approximate location derived from IP address, performance signals, and diagnostics.</p>
      <p>This information may be used to understand traffic, improve site performance, detect abuse, and measure general site activity.</p>

      <h3>Cookies and similar technologies</h3>
      <p>The site and its service providers may use cookies, pixels, local storage, or similar technologies to keep the site working, remember preferences, measure performance, support advertising, understand reader behavior, and manage tools such as notifications or embedded media.</p>
      <p>You can limit or block cookies in your browser settings, but some site features may work differently if you do.</p>

      <h3>Advertising partners and third-party ad networks</h3>
      <p>If advertising appears on the site, advertising providers may collect or receive information through cookies, identifiers, IP-based data, or related tools to serve ads, measure ad performance, prevent invalid activity, and manage ad delivery.</p>
      <p>If advertising services are used, third-party vendors, including Google, may use cookies to serve ads based on a user's prior visits to this site or other websites. Google's advertising cookies can help Google and its partners show ads based on visits to this site and across the internet, and users may be able to adjust personalized advertising choices through Google's ad settings.</p>
      <p>Other third-party ad networks or vendors may also use cookies or similar technologies if they are active on the site.</p>
      <p>The site does not promise advertising approval, ad availability, or personalized advertising choices in every region or context.</p>

      <h3>Embedded media and external platforms</h3>
      <p>Stories may include embedded video, social media posts, maps, documents, or other outside content. When you interact with embedded content, the third-party platform may collect information under its own privacy practices.</p>

      <h3>Shopify and site operations</h3>
      <p>The site runs on Shopify infrastructure and may use Shopify-powered forms, theme features, cookies, hosting, analytics-related functions, and operational tools. If payments, support tools, or other platform features are active, those features may involve additional data processing by Shopify or its partners.</p>

      <h3>How information may be used</h3>
      <p>Information may be used to operate the site, review tips, answer messages, send updates, investigate corrections, verify reporting, moderate submissions, analyze traffic, support advertising systems, improve reliability, prevent abuse, and comply with legal obligations.</p>

      <h3>When information may be shared</h3>
      <p>Information may be shared with hosting providers, Shopify, email or newsletter vendors, analytics providers, advertising partners, notification services, reader-support tools, anti-spam or security services, legal advisors, or authorities where required by law or reasonably necessary to protect rights, safety, or the public interest.</p>

      <h3>Data retention</h3>
      <p>Information may be kept for as long as reasonably needed for reporting, corrections, legal review, site operations, security, analytics, or recordkeeping. Tip submissions and correction requests may be retained even when they do not lead to publication.</p>

      <h3>Security limitations</h3>
      <p>No website, inbox, form, or online submission method is perfectly secure. The site tries to operate responsibly, but it cannot guarantee that information will never be intercepted, accessed, or misused.</p>

      <h3>Children's privacy</h3>
      <p>The site is intended for a general audience and is not designed as a children's service. If a parent or guardian believes a child submitted personal information through the site, they may use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page to request review.</p>

      <h3>Your choices</h3>
      <p>You can choose not to submit information, unsubscribe from emails where available, adjust browser cookie settings, and limit your use of embedded or third-party tools. Privacy rights vary by location, and the site may ask for information needed to verify a request before acting on it.</p>

      <h3>Contact path</h3>
      <p>For privacy questions, use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page. Related pages include <a href="{{ terms_url }}">Terms of Use</a>, <a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a>, and <a href="{{ legal_url }}">Legal and Advertising</a>.</p>

    {% when 'terms' %}
      <h2>Acceptance of terms</h2>
      <p>By using this site, you agree to these Terms of Use. If you do not agree, do not use the site.</p>

      <h3>Journalistic and informational purpose</h3>
      <p>The site exists for journalistic, informational, and editorial purposes. Content may include reporting, commentary, public records, allegations, outside sources, reader-submitted material, and developing facts that can change over time.</p>

      <h3>No professional advice</h3>
      <p>Nothing on the site is legal, financial, medical, security, or professional advice. You are responsible for how you use the information you read here.</p>

      <h3>User submissions and tips</h3>
      <p>You may submit information, documents, images, videos, links, corrections, or other material through the site. By submitting material, you confirm that you have the right to share it and grant this publication permission to review, verify, edit, publish, display, excerpt, archive, and use the material in connection with reporting, editorial review, and site operations.</p>
      <p>Submission does not guarantee publication, response, compensation, confidentiality, or ongoing storage.</p>

      <h3>Prohibited submissions and conduct</h3>
      <p>You may not use the site to submit or distribute false claims, doxxing material, threats, malware, spam, unlawful content, exploitative material, hate content, harassment, copyrighted material you do not have the right to share, private credentials, or material involving minors in a sexual or abusive context.</p>
      <p>You also may not use the site to interfere with its operation, scrape it in violation of law, impersonate others, or attempt to manipulate editorial decisions through abuse or fraud.</p>

      <h3>Intellectual property</h3>
      <p>Unless otherwise stated, original site content belongs to this publication or the applicable rights holder. Limited quoting and linking may be permitted where allowed by law, but wholesale copying, scraping, mirroring, resale, or redistribution of substantial site content is not allowed without permission.</p>

      <h3>External links and embedded content</h3>
      <p>The site may link to or embed third-party content. Those outside services are governed by their own terms and policies, not these terms.</p>

      <h3>Advertising and sponsor content</h3>
      <p>The site may publish paid placements, sponsorships, affiliate links, or other monetized content. Those arrangements do not give outside parties control over editorial coverage or corrections.</p>

      <h3>No guarantee of availability or accuracy</h3>
      <p>The site aims to report carefully, but it does not guarantee uninterrupted availability, complete accuracy at all times, or a perfect record in fast-moving situations. Content may change, be corrected, or be removed without prior notice.</p>

      <h3>Limitation of liability</h3>
      <p>To the fullest extent permitted by law, use of the site is at your own risk. The site and its operators are not liable for losses or damages arising from your reliance on the site, inability to access the site, third-party links, user submissions, or service interruptions.</p>

      <h3>Changes to terms</h3>
      <p>These terms may be updated from time to time. Continued use of the site after updates means you accept the revised terms.</p>

      <h3>Contact path</h3>
      <p>For questions about these terms, use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page. Related pages include <a href="{{ privacy_url }}">Privacy Policy</a>, <a href="{{ copyright_url }}">Copyright / DMCA Policy</a>, and <a href="{{ legal_url }}">Legal and Advertising</a>.</p>

    {% when 'advertise' %}
      <h2>Why sponsor this publication</h2>
      <p>Our audience comes to the site for breaking news, public accountability, investigative reporting, civil rights coverage, crime and community safety context, corruption reporting, cyber crime coverage, fraud reporting, and documentary-style public-interest storytelling.</p>
      <p>For mission-aligned brands, organizations, local businesses, civic groups, legal services, cybersecurity services, public-interest campaigns, creators, and documentary projects, sponsorship can be a way to appear alongside serious reporting without blurring the line between journalism and promotion.</p>

      <h3>Audience alignment</h3>
      <p>The site is built for readers who care about what happened, why it matters, and how power, evidence, and public records shape the story. Sponsors should fit that environment and respect reader trust.</p>

      <h3>Possible sponsorship and advertising options</h3>
      <p>Depending on the site's active features and editorial judgment, opportunities may include display sponsorship, newsletter sponsorship, clearly labeled sponsored messages or sponsored posts, and broader brand partnership inquiries.</p>
      <p>Availability can change based on traffic, site format, editorial needs, brand safety, platform policies, and technical setup.</p>

      <h3>Editorial independence</h3>
      <p>Paid placements are labeled. Sponsorship does not buy editorial coverage, favorable reporting, story removal, or influence over corrections.</p>
      <p>Sponsors do not control what stories are pursued, how facts are presented, or whether a correction is made.</p>

      <h3>Ad quality standards</h3>
      <p>We may reject ads or sponsorships that mislead readers, promote scams, illegal products, unsafe behavior, hate, harassment, adult sexual content, weapons, illegal drugs, extremist propaganda, or exploitative material.</p>
      <p>The site may also reject advertisers that impersonate public agencies or news organizations, create confusion between journalism and promotion, or conflict with reader trust and editorial independence.</p>

      <h3>Clear labeling</h3>
      <p>Sponsored placements should be identifiable to readers. The site aims to keep commercial material distinct from editorial reporting, navigation, and reader-service functions.</p>

      <h3>No guaranteed outcomes</h3>
      <p>The site does not guarantee traffic, conversions, publication, editorial attention, search visibility, ad-platform approval, ad inventory, or long-term sponsor availability.</p>
      <p>Submitting an inquiry also does not guarantee acceptance.</p>

      <h3>What to include in an inquiry</h3>
      <p>A useful inquiry may include your name, organization, website, contact information, campaign goals, preferred placement type, timing, target audience, budget range, and any creative or landing-page details you want reviewed.</p>

      <h3>Contact path</h3>
      <p>For sponsorship and advertising inquiries, use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page. Related policy pages include <a href="{{ legal_url }}">Legal and Advertising</a> and <a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a>.</p>

    {% when 'copyright' %}
      <h2>Site content ownership</h2>
      <p>Unless otherwise stated, original site content is owned by this publication or the applicable rights holder. That can include articles, headlines, original graphics, page copy, layout elements, original photos or videos, and other original editorial material.</p>
      <p>Third-party material remains the property of its respective owner.</p>

      <h3>Limited sharing and fair use</h3>
      <p>Readers may link to public pages on the site. Short excerpts may be quoted for commentary, criticism, research, or news discussion where permitted by law and accompanied by attribution when practical.</p>
      <p>Substantial copying, mirroring, scraping, resale, or redistribution of site content is not allowed without permission unless the law clearly permits it.</p>

      <h3>User-submitted material responsibilities</h3>
      <p>If you submit material to the site, you represent that you have the right to share it and that doing so does not knowingly violate another person's rights.</p>
      <p>Submission does not guarantee publication, payment, credit, confidentiality, or a response.</p>

      <h3>Copyright complaint process</h3>
      <p>If you believe material on the site infringes your copyright, send a copyright complaint through the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page unless a dedicated copyright channel is later published.</p>
      <p>Your notice should identify the copyrighted work, the allegedly infringing material, the exact page URL, your ownership or authority to act, and the basis for the complaint.</p>

      <h3>Information required for a DMCA notice</h3>
      <ol>
        <li>Your full legal name and contact information</li>
        <li>Your organization, if applicable</li>
        <li>Identification of the copyrighted work</li>
        <li>The URL of the allegedly infringing material</li>
        <li>A description of where the material appears</li>
        <li>A statement explaining your ownership or authorization to act</li>
        <li>A good-faith statement that the use is not authorized by the copyright owner, its agent, or the law</li>
        <li>A statement that the information in the notice is accurate</li>
        <li>A statement made under penalty of perjury that you are the copyright owner or authorized to act on the owner's behalf</li>
        <li>Your physical or electronic signature</li>
      </ol>

      <h3>Counter-notices</h3>
      <p>If material is removed and you believe that happened because of mistake or misidentification, you may submit a counter-notice where applicable. A counter-notice should identify the removed material, explain the basis for contesting the claim, include your contact information, and include the statements and consent required by applicable law.</p>
      <p>If you are unsure about the legal consequences of sending a notice or counter-notice, speak with a lawyer. This page is not legal advice.</p>

      <h3>Repeat infringement</h3>
      <p>The site may restrict or decline submissions from repeat infringers or from parties who repeatedly misuse the copyright complaint process.</p>

      <h3>Neutral review and public-interest context</h3>
      <p>A copyright complaint does not automatically require removal. The site may consider context such as fair use, public-interest reporting, quotation, embedding, commentary, or other lawful uses before deciding how to respond.</p>

      <h3>Contact path</h3>
      <p>For copyright complaints or questions, use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page and clearly label the message as a copyright or DMCA matter. Related pages include <a href="{{ terms_url }}">Terms of Use</a> and <a href="{{ privacy_url }}">Privacy Policy</a>.</p>

    {% when 'source-attribution' %}
      <h2>How We Use Sources</h2>
      <p>Our reporting is built around transparency. We want readers to understand where information comes from, what has been verified, what remains alleged, and what source material shaped each story.</p>
      <p>We use public records, court filings, official statements, agency releases, documents, interviews, reader-submitted materials, and verified open-source information when reporting public-interest stories. When a story relies heavily on an official release, public filing, or government source, we identify that source where practical and avoid presenting official claims as independently proven facts unless they have been verified through additional reliable material.</p>
      <p>Sources may include court filings, indictments, complaints, plea agreements, judgments, sentencing records, docket entries, official statements, public records, audits, meeting records, public notices, reader-submitted material, verified open-source material, and prior reporting when credited.</p>

      <h3>Allegations, Charges, and Claims</h3>
      <p>If information comes from an official statement, we label it as an official statement. If information comes from a court filing, lawsuit, indictment, complaint, or other allegation-based record, we do not treat it as a final finding simply because it appears in a public document.</p>
      <p>We aim to distinguish what is alleged, charged, admitted, found by a court or agency, disputed, or still unverified. Criminal charges and civil lawsuits are not final findings, and defendants are presumed innocent unless and until proven guilty in court where applicable.</p>

      <h3>Reader-Submitted Material</h3>
      <p>Reader-submitted material can help identify leads, documents, timelines, public-interest concerns, or missing context, but submission does not guarantee publication, response, confidentiality, payment, legal protection, or investigation.</p>
      <p>Material may be declined if it is unverifiable, unlawfully obtained, exploitative, irrelevant, misleading, private without meaningful public-interest value, or likely to place someone at risk. We may use reader-submitted material as a lead, background context, verification target, or not at all.</p>

      <h3>Corrections and Updates</h3>
      <p>If a source changes, is corrected, contradicted, withdrawn, or clarified, we may update the story, add an editor's note, publish a correction, or follow up with additional reporting. Readers who see a sourcing issue should review our <a href="{{ corrections_url }}">Corrections Policy</a> and use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page to send evidence-backed concerns.</p>
      <p>Related pages include <a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a>, <a href="{{ public_records_url }}">Public Records Policy</a>, and <a href="{{ non_affiliation_url }}">Non-Affiliation Disclaimer</a>.</p>

    {% when 'public-records' %}
      <h2>What We Mean by Public Records</h2>
      <p>Public records are central to accountability journalism. They help readers evaluate claims, understand institutions, follow public decisions, and see how power is used.</p>
      <p>We use public records to report on crime, corruption, civil rights, cyber crime, public safety, government accountability, white-collar crime, court proceedings, institutional failures, and other matters of public interest.</p>
      <p>Public records may include court filings, docket entries, government audits, budgets, contracts, procurement documents, meeting records, agency statements, inspection reports, enforcement notices, lawsuits, complaints, judgments, settlements, sentencing records, public datasets, registries, corporate filings, licensing records, and public statements.</p>

      <h3>How We Use Public Records</h3>
      <p>A public document is not automatically repeated in full. We consider relevance, privacy, public-interest value, and potential harm before deciding how much detail to publish and how to frame it for readers.</p>
      <p>Our goal is to explain what the record says, who created it, when it was filed, published, or updated, whether it contains allegations, findings, admissions, or disputed claims, what context readers need, and what remains unresolved. Public records can contain errors, omissions, one-sided claims, outdated information, or language that needs added context.</p>

      <h3>Privacy and Public Interest</h3>
      <p>We may avoid or limit details involving minors, victims, private individuals, addresses, phone numbers, personal identifiers, medical information, financial details, or other sensitive material unless there is a clear public-interest reason to publish them.</p>
      <p>This site does not publish private information for harassment, retaliation, embarrassment, or shock value. Public availability alone is not the only test; editorial judgment matters.</p>

      <h3>Requests, Tips, and Documents</h3>
      <p>Readers may send records, tips, links, or supporting documents that help us verify a story or identify gaps in the public record. Submission does not guarantee publication, response, confidentiality, payment, legal protection, or investigation.</p>
      <p>Material may be reviewed for relevance, authenticity, public-interest value, privacy concerns, and safety concerns before it shapes coverage. Some documents may be used as background only, quoted selectively, or declined altogether.</p>

      <h3>Updates and Corrections</h3>
      <p>If a record changes, is corrected, sealed, contradicted, or later turns out to lack important context, coverage may be updated. We may revise language, add clarifications, publish a correction, or add an editor's note when readers need to understand what changed.</p>
      <p>Related pages include <a href="{{ source_attribution_url }}">Source Attribution Policy</a>, <a href="{{ corrections_url }}">Corrections Policy</a>, and <a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a>.</p>

    {% when 'non-affiliation' %}
      <h2>No Government or Law-Enforcement Authority</h2>
      <p>This site is an independent journalism and public-accountability publication. We are not affiliated with the FBI, DOJ, any court, police department, prosecutor's office, government agency, intelligence agency, emergency service, political campaign, or law-enforcement organization.</p>
      <p>We report, analyze, verify, summarize, and publish public-interest information using public records, official statements, court filings, documents, reader-submitted material, and other source material when appropriate. We do not act on behalf of any agency or institution.</p>
      <p>This site does not enforce laws, prosecute cases, represent victims, defendants, witnesses, agencies, or courts, provide emergency response, accept official crime reports on behalf of law enforcement, or provide legal, safety, financial, or professional advice.</p>
      <p>If there is immediate danger or an emergency, contact local emergency services.</p>

      <h3>Use of Official Sources</h3>
      <p>Some articles may rely on official public source material, agency releases, court documents, public records, public statements, or government databases. Attribution to an official source does not mean endorsement, affiliation, approval, or institutional partnership.</p>
      <p>Charges, complaints, indictments, lawsuits, agency claims, and official statements should be understood according to their legal and factual status. Allegations are not proven findings, and an official source is not the same thing as independent verification.</p>

      <h3>Editorial Independence</h3>
      <p>Advertising, sponsorships, affiliate links, donations, outside organizations, public agencies, private companies, political groups, or source providers do not control story selection, conclusions, corrections, or editorial standards.</p>
      <p>Editorial judgment remains with the publication. We may quote, analyze, challenge, verify, summarize, or decline official claims based on the available evidence and public-interest value.</p>

      <h3>Reader Submissions</h3>
      <p>Reader submission does not create a confidential relationship, attorney-client relationship, source-protection guarantee, payment agreement, or promise of publication. We do not guarantee response, anonymity, confidentiality, legal protection, or investigation.</p>
      <p>Material may be declined if it is unsafe, unverifiable, irrelevant, unlawfully obtained, exploitative, misleading, or not in the public interest.</p>

      <h3>Contact</h3>
      <p>For general questions about the site or its policies, use the <a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a> page. Related pages include <a href="{{ legal_url }}">Legal and Advertising</a>, <a href="{{ source_attribution_url }}">Source Attribution Policy</a>, and <a href="{{ public_records_url }}">Public Records Policy</a>.</p>

    {% when 'trust-policies' %}
      <h2>Editorial Accountability</h2>
      <p>This page brings together the editorial, corrections, source, records, privacy, advertising, and legal policies that guide this publication. Our goal is to make standards easy to find so readers can evaluate how reporting is sourced, corrected, reviewed, and separated from advertising or outside influence.</p>
      <p>Our reporting is built around verification, context, restraint, and corrections when the record changes. These pages explain how we separate allegations from confirmed facts, how we handle updates, and how readers can raise concerns.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="{{ standards_url }}">Editorial Standards</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ corrections_url }}">Corrections Policy</a></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Sources and Public Records</h3>
      <p>Much of our reporting relies on public records, court filings, official statements, source documents, and reader-submitted material. These policies explain how we identify source material, avoid presenting allegations as findings, and make clear that this publication is independent from government agencies, courts, law enforcement, and source providers.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="{{ source_attribution_url }}">Source Attribution Policy</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ public_records_url }}">Public Records Policy</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ non_affiliation_url }}">Non-Affiliation Disclaimer</a></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Legal, Privacy, and Advertising</h3>
      <p>These pages explain how the site handles privacy, user submissions, intellectual property, advertising, sponsorship, affiliate relationships, and the separation between editorial judgment and monetization.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="{{ legal_url }}">Legal and Advertising</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ privacy_url }}">Privacy Policy</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ terms_url }}">Terms of Use</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ copyright_url }}">Copyright / DMCA Policy</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ advertise_url }}">Advertise / Sponsor</a></li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Reader Contact</h3>
      <p>Readers can contact the publication about corrections, source questions, rights concerns, advertising inquiries, or public-interest tips. Submission does not guarantee publication, response, confidentiality, payment, legal protection, or investigation.</p>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="{{ contact_url }}">Contact</a></li>
        <li><a href="{{ submit_tip_url }}">Submit a Tip</a></li>
      </ul>
  {% endcase %}
{% endcapture %}

<article class="newsroom-page newsroom-page--{{ newsroom_page_kind }}">
  <header class="newsroom-page__header">
    <p class="newsroom-page__kicker">Publisher Information</p>
    <h1 class="newsroom-page__title">{{ page.title }}</h1>
    {% if newsroom_page_lede != blank %}
      <p class="newsroom-page__lede">{{ newsroom_page_lede | strip }}</p>
    {% endif %}
  </header>

  <div class="newsroom-page__body rte">
    {% if newsroom_page_fallback != blank %}
      {{ newsroom_page_fallback }}
    {% elsif page.content != blank %}
      {{ page.content }}
    {% endif %}
  </div>

  {% unless newsroom_page_kind == 'privacy' or newsroom_page_kind == 'terms' or newsroom_page_kind == 'copyright' %}
    {% include 'submit-tip-cta' %}
  {% endunless %}
</article>

